article.headline: Arizona State 75, Oregon State 73
article.story: TEMPE, Ariz. (AP) -- Bryson Krueger was told to shoot more. He listened, and it paid off big for Arizona State. Krueger's 21 points offset what could have been a disappointing night for Ike Diogu, and the Sun Devils hung on to beat Oregon State 75-73 Thursday night after blowing an 18-point lead. Diogu, who leads the NCAA in free throws attempted and made, had 25 points -- in double figures for the 85th consecutive game -- but missed a career-high seven foul shots. The win wasn't locked down until Krueger threw a floor-length in-bounds pass to Serge Angounou, who dribbled out the final three seconds. "Serge kind of stepped in there and picked it up," Diogu said. "Bryson, he helped us get that big first-half lead." Krueger, who tied his career high with five 3-pointers, had 16 points in the first half. "They've been telling me to be more aggressive, and we put in a couple of things to get the guards more action," Krueger said. Jason Braxton had a season-high 11 points for the Sun Devils (17-9, 6-8 Pac-10). The Beavers (14-10, 6-7) rallied from a 44-26 deficit behind David Lucas, who had 26 points and 13 rebounds, and Jason Fontenot. "It's tough, man," Lucas said. "We had a lot of energy before the game, and we got to the first half and we just didn't come out like we needed to." Fontenot scored 13 of his 19 points in the second half, when Oregon State surged from a 44-26 deficit to a 63-62 lead on Lucas' three-point play with 6:23 left. "Our offense pretty much runs around David, and once he gets touches it creates a lot of chances for the guards to get jump shots, and that's what we did," Fontenot said about the rally. "A lot of penetration." But the Sun Devils answered, regaining the lead when Angounou drove the key for a dunk with 5:47 to go. When Fontenot missed a shot the next trip upcourt, Angounou, who had seven of his eight rebounds in the second half, got the carom and Krueger made his last 3-pointer with 5:20 remaining. The Beavers came back to tie it at 67 on Nick DeWitz's 16-footer with 3:28 left, but Arizona State opened breathing room on a jumper by Angounou and Braxton's free throw. With 24 seconds left, DeWitz cut the gap to 72-71 with a 3-pointer, but Kevin Kruger made three free throws down the stretch to keep the Beavers (0-6) winless in Pac-10 road games. "This league is tough," Arizona State coach Rob Evans said. "Tough to win on the road and tough to win at home. We've found that out." Both teams shot poorly in the first half, and the game was tight until Krueger scored 11 points in a 2:20 span, giving the Sun Devils a 33-18 lead. His last two baskets were a jumper after rebounding a missed free throw by Diogu with 5:49 left in the half, and a 3-pointer 47 seconds later. That was Arizona State's biggest lead until Diogu made a 14-foot jumper with 2 seconds left after recovering his own blocked shot, opening a 42-26 halftime lead. "You can't dig such a big hole," Beavers coach Jay John said. "When you do that, your margin of error in the second half becomes so razor-thin that everything has to go your way, and that is not the reality of life."
